tened form of French   Lamontagne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mountain","meanings":["English (Yorkshire; of Norman origin): topographic name from Middle English <i>mountaine</i> ‘mountain’ (Old French <i>montagne</i>). See   Montagne  .","Irish: either of Norman origin, as 1 above, or a variant of   Manton  .","English: variant of <b>Monkton</b> a habitational name from Monkton (Kent, Somerset), Moor Monkton and Nun Monkton (Yorkshire), Bishop Monkton (Yorkshire), or any of numerous other places called Monkton, named with Old English <i>munuc</i> ‘monk’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]},{"name":"Lamontagne","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Lucien, Marcel, Emile, Pierre, Aime, Andre, Fernand, Normand, Gaston, Ovide, Achille.","French:","habitational name for someone from any of several places called La Montagne, or a variant of the topographic name   Montagne   1, with fused feminine definite article <i>la</i>."]}]},{"name":"Marguerite","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Margaret  , also used in the English-speaking world, where its use has been reinforced by the fact that the name was adopted in the 19th century for a garden flower, a large cultivated variety of daisy. <i>Margaret</i> was earlier used in English as a dialect word denoting the ox-eye daisy, and the French equivalent was borrowed into English just in time to catch the vogue for deriving girls' names from vocabulary words denoting flowers.  See also  Daisy ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Marguerite de Mortagne was born from 1303 to 1315, in Mortagne-du-Nord, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France, her father, Robert de MORTAGNE, was 35 and her mother, Marguerite De Ghistelles, was 30. She had at least 1 daughter with Jean II de LONGUEVAL. She died in 1348, in Longueval, Somme, Picardie, France."},"et":{"BET 1303 AND 1315–1348":"1303 kuni 1315–1348","1303–1348":"1303–1348","1350